    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-08-02T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-08-02T15:00:00-05:00" n="492"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d492">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">560.AL/8–147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Consulate at Geneva</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-08-02T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 2, 1947—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>944. For Clayton from Wood.<note n="1" xml:id="d492fn1">C. Tyler Wood, Deputy to
                        the Assistant Secretary of State for Economic Affairs.</note> Discussed with
                    Nitze problems raised <gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 802 Aug 1.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d492fn2">Not printed, but see memorandum of conversation of
                        July 31, <ref target="#pg_969">p. 969</ref>. 560.AL/8–247: Telegram</note>
                    Following our tentative thoughts: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Apparent Br econ and domestic political situation such that we must
                            accede their demands for permission to discriminate.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Believe you and US <gloss target="#t_Del1">Del</gloss> best position
                            determine technique (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) which would do least
                            damage to <gloss target="#t_ITO1">ITO</gloss> and (<hi rend="italic"
                                >b</hi>) also which would not destroy chances TA renewal and
                            acceptance <gloss target="#t_ITO1">ITO</gloss> by Congress.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>However suggest consideration alternative: That discrimination would
                            be permitted on showing of need and fact, and with arrangements for
                            consultation, although clearly understood that country proposing
                            discrimination would have unilateral authority to (<hi rend="italic"
                                >a</hi>) determine facts and need and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) put
                            into force discrimination. Belief that this approach might (<hi
                                rend="italic">a</hi>) be more palatable to US interests and Congress
                            and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) prevent oblique use discriminatory
                            authority for purely protective purposes. [Wood.]</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
